No coverage tests for newly created objects.

Doing iterative testing is important to catch bugs early and detect
erroneous behaviour.

Let's add some simple tests to ensure code is correct thus far.

This will help catching bugs and unit issues more easily and timely.

There is a weird behaviour found while testing. The plan IDs are
not initialised within the constructor and all plans have a separate
variable called ID.

When these plans are created using Insurance plan as the object,
the ID defaults to 0. The equals method then works weirdly because
then all plans created through polymorphism has the same ID.

Let's make the ID global variable only appear inside of the
InsurancePlan object with an invalid id and the variable is then
declared differently in each class.

This allows the equals method to work as intended in future with
polymorphism which should allow any checking of duplicate plans to
be more correct

Claims and Insurance uses the same Exception when throwing errors.

This makes it difficult for the developer to throw different
error messages when either one fails as both are dependent on the
same Exception object type.

Let's add separate Exception type objects to both such that
different error messages can be shown to the user in case of wrong
input or execution.

This will also free up namespace cluttering in future development.

Some weird behaviours only found during the testing phase.

The persisting issue is that the models point to the same
insurance plan manager object when manipulating one of the models.
In the actual application this is not an issue as only one model can
exist at a time. However, in the testing environment, there are
two models existing at once.

This creates weird behaviours when comparing the insurance plan
managers between 2 models as deleting a claim in one model also
deletes it in the second model, throwing errors in the test.

Let's fix this by creating a new object using the JSON string
methods in the insurance plan manager class.

This will create 2 separate objects preventing the manipulation
in one of the models to affect the second, allowing the tests to
pass.

I forgot to add the most important part, the deletion from the
expected model...

commitResults.messageTitle: Add better functionality to close claim and insurance plan manager
commitResults.messageBody:
There was a bug where more than 1 claim could not be added. This is
because the insurance plan manager used the equals method to check
if the plan exists in the manager, thus, after the first check it
becomes impossible to "get" the manager as the created instance by
the factory is no longer the same as that inside the manager.

Let's change the getting process here to be a little more lax
to prevent such bugs.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix testing methods for Insurance and Claim Commands
commitResults.messageBody:
The testing utilities do not support comparison of states of
InsurancePlansManager objects as we purposefully implemented it
as a mutable object and did not include this object to the client's
equals method.

This causes weird testing behaviours as the expected and intended
models used in assertCommandSuccess methods do not really check if
the two InsurancePlansManager objects are indeed the same.

Let's introduce a new testing utility to check for changes in
InsurancePlanManager objects instead of clients.

This should make the testing alot easier and accurate for commands
related to Insurances and Claims.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix tests using the new testing utility methods
commitResults.messageBody:
While using the new tests, uncovered a bug inside close claim
command as the plan marks the object itself as false. This may cause
weird behaviours if say, two claims with same claimIds exist under
different plans.

Let's change this to ensure only the claim inside of the insurance
plan.

This should get rid of any weird behaviours.

The following tests were also updated using the new test utility.

- AddInsuranceCommandTest
- CloseClaimCommandTest
- DeleteClaimCommandTest
